04668nam a22006015i 9780520959279DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20152015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209592797 a10.1525/97805209592792doi  a(DE-B1597)519362  a(OCoLC)903016083  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aJV6483b.D74 2015eb 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a305.9/069122231 aDreby, Joanna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEveryday Illegal :bWhen Policies Undermine Immigrant Families /cJoanna Dreby. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: Legal Status in Family Contexts -- t2. Nervios: On the Threat of Deportation -- t3. Stuck: Dependence in Intimate Relationships -- t4. It's Not Fair: The Pecking Order in Immigrant Families -- t5. Stigma: Illegality in Different Immigrant Neighborhoods -- t6. Conclusion: Reframing Illegality -- tAppendix: Talking to Kids: Methodological Issues -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat does it mean to be an illegal immigrant, or the child of immigrants, in this era of restrictive immigration laws in the United States? As lawmakers and others struggle to respond to the changing landscape of immigration, the effects of policies on people's daily lives are all too often overlooked. In Everyday Illegal, award-winning author Joanna Dreby recounts the stories of children and parents in eighty-one families to show what happens when a restrictive immigration system emphasizes deportation over legalization. Interweaving her own experiences, Dreby illustrates how bitter strains can arise in relationships when spouses have different legal status. She introduces us to "suddenly single mothers" who struggle to place food on the table and pay rent after their husbands have been deported. Taking us into the homes and schools of children living in increasingly vulnerable circumstances, she presents families that are divided internally, with some children having legal status while their siblings are undocumented. Even children who are U.S. citizens regularly associate immigration with illegality. With vivid ethnographic details and a striking narrative, Everyday Illegal forces us to confront the devastating impacts of our immigration policies as seen through the eyes of children and their families. As legal status influences identity formation, alters the division of power within families, and affects the opportunities children have outside the home, it becomes a growing source of inequality that ultimately touches us all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aChildren of immigrantsxCase studiesxUnited States. 0aChildren of immigrantszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aIllegal aliensxCase studiesxUnited States. 0aIllegal alienszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aImmigrantsxCase studiesxFamily relationshipsxUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxFamily relationshipszUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311062111208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520959279423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520959279.jpg  a978-3-11-062111-2  UC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-0663